<taxonomicName id="7CFC4D27C4771C2EFC31FB3BFAF7FEBC" authority="Tang &amp; Ho (2020)" authorityName="Tang &amp; Ho" authorityYear="2020" box="[910,1298,331,357]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Plectranthias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="purpuralepis">
<emphasis id="8988EAB6C4771C2EFC31FB3BFBDFFEBC" box="[910,1082,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">P. purpuralepis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="DF6D4B55C4771C2EFBFFFB3BFAF7FEBC" author="Tang, C. N. &amp; Lai, N. W. &amp; Ho, H. C." box="[1088,1298,331,357]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" pagination="508 - 522" refId="ref75351" refString="Tang, C. N., Lai, N. W. &amp; Ho, H. C. (2020) Plectranthias purpuralepis sp. nov., a new anthiine perchlet from northern Taiwan (Perciformes: Serranidae). Zootaxa, 4780 (3), 508 - 522. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4780.3.4" type="journal article" year="2020">Tang &amp; Ho (2020)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. It is readily distinguished from these species in having the fourth (versus third) dorsal spine longest, and 13 unbranched pectoral rays (versus mostly branched rays, 
<quantity id="7C049B41C4771C2EFD96FBE3FD86FE74" box="[553,611,403,429]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.302" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" unit="in" value="13.0">13 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName id="7CFC4D27C4771C2EFDD4FBE3FD0DFE74" authorityName="Randall" authorityYear="1980" box="[619,744,403,429]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Plectranthias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="wheeleri">
<emphasis id="8988EAB6C4771C2EFDD4FBE3FD0DFE74" box="[619,744,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">P. wheeleri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<quantity id="7C049B41C4771C2EFD47FBE3FCD7FE74" box="[760,818,403,429]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.556" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" unit="in" value="14.0">14 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName id="7CFC4D27C4771C2EFC85FBE3FC4BFE74" authorityName="Randall" authorityYear="1980" box="[826,942,403,429]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Plectranthias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="helenae">
<emphasis id="8988EAB6C4771C2EFC85FBE3FC4BFE74" box="[826,942,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">P. helenae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="7CFC4D27C4771C2EFC58FBE3FB8BFE74" authorityName="Wada, Senou &amp; Motomura" authorityYear="2018" box="[999,1134,403,429]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Plectranthias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="maekawa">
<emphasis id="8988EAB6C4771C2EFC58FBE3FB8BFE74" box="[999,1134,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">P. maekawa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<quantity id="7C049B41C4771C2EFB11FBE2FAF7FE74" box="[1198,1298,402,429]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.683" metricValueMax="3.81" metricValueMin="3.556" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" unit="in" value="14.5" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="14.0">14–15 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName id="7CFC4D27C4771C2EFAA5FBE3FF29FE08" authorityName="Tang &amp; Ho" authorityYear="2020" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Plectranthias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="purpuralepis">
<emphasis id="8988EAB6C4771C2EFAA5FBE3FF29FE08" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">P. purpuralepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). It further differs from 
<taxonomicName id="7CFC4D27C4771C2EFE5DFBC7FD75FE08" authorityName="Tang &amp; Ho" authorityYear="2020" box="[482,656,439,465]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Plectranthias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="purpuralepis">
<emphasis id="8988EAB6C4771C2EFE5DFBC7FD75FE08" box="[482,656,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">P. purpuralepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having fewer segmented dorsal rays (15 versus 16–17) and fewer tubed lateral-line scales (29–30 versus 33–36). The purple-grey blotches on the head and body following preservation are unusual for the genus. Similar coloration is otherwise known only from 
<taxonomicName id="7CFC4D27C4771C2EFB98FB8FFB31FDC0" authorityName="Tang &amp; Ho" authorityYear="2020" box="[1063,1236,511,537]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Serranidae" genus="Plectranthias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="purpuralepis">
<emphasis id="8988EAB6C4771C2EFB98FB8FFB31FDC0" box="[1063,1236,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">P. purpuralepis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="C3EB7634C4771C2EFAA5FB8FFA89FDC0" box="[1306,1388,511,537]" name="Taiwan" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
and represents a possible synapomorphy. If so, the two species display an anti-equatorial distribution pattern (
<bibRefCitation id="DF6D4B55C4771C2EFAFCF853FF36FDB8" author="Randall, J. E." pageId="32" pageNumber="33" pagination="197 - 209" refId="ref74106" refString="Randall, J. E. (1982) Examples of antitropical and antiequatorial distribution of Indo-west-Pacific fishes. Pacific Science, 35, 197 - 209." type="journal article" year="1982">Randall 1982</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BB4336A4C4771C2EFF78F81BFDF4FCE0" blockId="32.[151,1437,150,825]" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">
Our account for this species is based on a specimen collected in 
<quantity id="7C049B41C4771C2EFC11F81BFBCAFD5C" box="[942,1071,619,645]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.025" metricValueMax="3.07" metricValueMin="2.98" pageId="32" pageNumber="33" unit="m" value="302.5" valueMax="307.0" valueMin="298.0">298–307 m</quantity>
from a large seamount north of Middleton Reef on the Lord Howe Rise (
<figureCitation id="23C72A21C4771C2EFDDCF8FFFD20FD70" box="[611,709,655,681]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="32.[151,250,1787,1811]" captionTargetBox="[180,1408,855,1760]" captionTargetId="figure-336@32.[174,1413,849,1763]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURE 7. Australian distribution records for Plectranthias sp. 1 (open circle), P. bennetti (closed circle) and P. japonicus (closed triangles)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4471937" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4471937/files/figure.png" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Figure 7</figureCitation>
). The specimen is distorted, with its head displaced upwards and mouth wide open. Although an attempt was made to correct for distortion, some morphometric data for the specimen may not be accurate (
<tableCitation id="F67E031FC4771C2EFE02F8A7FDC6FD28" box="[445,547,727,753]" captionStart="TABLE 18" captionStartId="33.[151,239,151,175]" captionText="TABLE 18. Morphometric values for Plectranthias sp. 1, P. grahami n. sp. and P. moretonensis n. sp. expressed as percentages of SL. * indicates where a measurement could not be made, owing to damage." pageId="32" pageNumber="33">Table 18</tableCitation>
). The species also occurs on the Norfolk and Kermadec Ridges (
<bibRefCitation id="DF6D4B55C4771C2EFB49F8A7FF36FCCC" author="Williams, A. &amp; Gowlett-Holmes, K. &amp; Althaus, F." pageId="32" pageNumber="33" pagination="1 - 8" refId="ref76153" refString="Williams, A., Gowlett-Holmes, K. &amp; Althaus, F. (2006) Biodiversity survey of seamounts and slopes of the Norfolk Ridge and Lord Howe Rise. Final Report to the Department of the Environment and Heritage (National Oceans Office), i-vi + 1 - 203, Append. 1 - 8." type="book chapter" year="2006">
Williams 
<emphasis id="8988EAB6C4771C2EFADBF8A7FA78FD28" box="[1380,1437,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="32" pageNumber="33">et al.</emphasis>
2006
</bibRefCitation>
; C.D. Roberts, pers. comm.), and will be formally described by C.D. Roberts and A.C. Gill, based on specimens from the Kermadec Islands.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
